REG A+: KEY ELEMENTS

On March 25, 2015, the SEC issued final rules on Regulation A+, as mandated by the JOBS ACT, and the rules went into effect on June 19, 2015
Provides small cap issuers ability to raise up to $50 million in a 12-month period
Both accredited and non-accredited investors are permitted to participate with certain limitations
Can market in all 50 states, subject to state blue sky law compliance
Allows test the waters communications to determine investor appetite before filing an offering circular with the SEC.
Enables use of public channels such as email or social media to market an offering
Establishes reduced filing and compliance requirements for issuer as compared to a registered public offering
Non-accredited investors (in a Regulation A, Tier 2 offering): In the case of a non-accredited natural person, no more than 10 percent of the greater of his or her annual income and net worth, with annual income and net worth being calculated in the same manner as the “accredited investor” definition in Rule 501(a) under the Securities Act of 1933; and in the case of a non-accredited entity such as a corporation or trust, no more than 10 percent of the greater of the purchaser’s revenue or net assets (as of the purchaser’s most recent fiscal year end)

